hi this is @Mer Durer again

As I've stated in the healthcare subnet already today. I am here to showcase exploits on Bittensor's subnets in an effort to 1) Force subnet owners to improve, 2) Get validators to remove weights from faulty subnets and 3) instill at least some fear into subnet owners who are not properly updating or monitoring their own subnets. 

The next on my list is ZKTensor.

# ZKTensor

Zero-knowlege Machine learning means that when a machine learning model is run, it produces a proof as an output of the inference which can only be produced if the Machine Learning model was actually run with those inputs on THAT model.

Like the Healthcare subnet, getting ZK right on Bittensor would be amazing for the following reasons 1) other subnets could run verifiable ML algorithms and 2) Bittensor can be shown to do the exact same thing as other ML crypto's like Ritual.  

However, as we will see, this is not yet the case:

# Mechanism
ZKtensor works like this. 

1) The validators produce randomly generated inputs by sampling 3 random numbers.

https://github.com/zktensor/zktensor_subnet/blob/cc5e7fe50c8d214e2b8c9a1f5e9044c0ecbaa72d/neurons/_validator/validator_session.py#L268

2) The validators then broadcast those inputs + a model id (which never changes) to all the miners on the subnet.

https://github.com/zktensor/zktensor_subnet/blob/cc5e7fe50c8d214e2b8c9a1f5e9044c0ecbaa72d/neurons/_validator/validator_session.py#L268

3) The validators recieve the results from the miners and then verify them using an off-the-shelf ZK solver which proves that the miners produces the outputs by running the model with the specified ID.

https://github.com/zktensor/zktensor_subnet/blob/cc5e7fe50c8d214e2b8c9a1f5e9044c0ecbaa72d/neurons/_validator/validator_session.py#L239

4) The validators keep track of how often the Proofs are accurately produced; giving higher scores to miners that produce valid results and lower scores to miners that return invalid scores.

https://github.com/zktensor/zktensor_subnet/blob/cc5e7fe50c8d214e2b8c9a1f5e9044c0ecbaa72d/neurons/_validator/validator_session.py#L135

6) Eventually these scores are normalized and set on the chain.

https://github.com/zktensor/zktensor_subnet/blob/cc5e7fe50c8d214e2b8c9a1f5e9044c0ecbaa72d/neurons/_validator/validator_session.py#L171

# How to exploit.

There are two problems with this subnet.

1) The least worrying: the Subnet only produces 100^3 == 1M unique inputs. This can be easily solved by the subnet owner. However in the mean time an adversary needs only store all 1M possibly outputs and never run a model again.

https://github.com/zktensor/zktensor_subnet/blob/cc5e7fe50c8d214e2b8c9a1f5e9044c0ecbaa72d/neurons/_validator/validator_session.py#L268

2) The more worrying: The owner only provides 1 model type that the miners can run and it is very small. From the README: 
>. Right now, Only a single ZkSqrtRegressionModel is deployed in the deployment layer, miners will be asked to generate proof for the public inputs from the validators. This will not require that much computing power right now.

Because the number of models needed to run has not increased beyond 1 for >1 month and because this model is very small (requires less than 4GM of GPU ram, per the README), this means that this subnet is stupidly easy to mine, essentially free. 

Because of this, all of the miners never miss a query and after normalization all weights for all miners converges to exactly 1/n. This can be viewed by visiting the incentive curve on this link: https://taostats.io/subnets/netuid-28/

# Conclusion

ZKtensor is a good idea. However there has not been an update to this repo for over 1 month! With such obvious issues present on the subnet I would suggest that the validators move weights to other subnets until this owner adds additional functionality and proves it is worth 1 % of Bittensor's emission. In the mean time, the subnet produces nothing.

If you check out the btcli reference on https://docs.bittensor.com you'll be able to see an up to date listing of commands.  You can also use `btcli st -h` to get all of the options.  `btcli w overview` should show you what your current situation is; if a remove command isn't working, it's possible that you're running it referencing a coldkey that isn't actually the coldkey that's controlling the hotkey in question.  You can use `btcli w list` to list out all of your accounts; it'll show which coldkey(s) you have, and which hotkey(s) are associated with them. For those wondering why dereg keeps happening, look at the incentive distribution chart of this subnet vs others. It's very flat, i.e. nearly all miners have the exact same incentive score. It doesn't take much to go from the top of the pack to the back and therefore get dereg'd (the lowest incentive miners are replaced with new ones during registration)
Here's how that distribution looks on other subnets. Notice the curve. There is a substantial difference between those with a high incentive and the lowest.
The difference of 0.0001 incentive can be the difference of you being top vs bottom
